			<ns0:name>b...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/105821748722532785568/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">why not a function that can be invoked via gdb?  is it really needed programmatically?

is buffer_count the number of bytes or number of entries?  will we want other information eventually, e.g., some way to identify the type of memory object providing backing store (e.g., shm, mapped file, anonymous memory)?  MemoryMapRegion freezes the ABI and doesn't provide an easy way to extend it -- and this kind of call could be useful for more than debugging.  what is the return value?  what happens when the number of regions exceed buffer_count?

see http://www.gnu.org/software/hurd/gnumach-doc/Memory-Attributes.html#Memory-Attributes for a similar interface.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2013-04-03T19:59:28.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2013-04-03T19:59:28.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates /><ns0:title>Comment 1 by b...@google.com</ns0:title><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=3366#c1" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/3366/comments/full/1" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /></ns0:entry>